<subSubSection id="C37D656C744EFFE0C4E8FA55FCF9995D" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BD836E7744EFFE0C4E8FA55FCF9995D" blockId="1.[174,1233,1222,1857]" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">
Diagnosis. Both sexes of 
<taxonomicName id="4C674D64744EFFE0C630FA54FD0F9BFC" baseAuthorityName="Fallen" baseAuthorityYear="1817" box="[571,732,1478,1504]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Hammerschmidtia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ferruginea">
<emphasis id="B913EAF5744EFFE0C630FA54FD0F9BFC" box="[571,732,1478,1504]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">H. ferruginea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
clearly differ from 
<taxonomicName id="4C674D64744EFFE0C7DEFA54FB9D9BFC" authorityName="Stackelberg" authorityYear="1952" box="[981,1102,1479,1504]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Hammerschmidtia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ingrica">
<emphasis id="B913EAF5744EFFE0C7DEFA54FB9D9BFC" box="[981,1102,1479,1504]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">H. ingrica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="135C2A62744EFFE0C068FA55FB149BFD" box="[1123,1223,1478,1505]" captionStart="Figs 1–8" captionStartId="2.[166,205,1723,1745]" captionTargetBox="[166,1224,261,1679]" captionTargetId="figure-14@2.[166,1225,261,1679]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 1–8. Hammerschmidtia ferruginea (figs 1–4) from Rivne Region (Ukraine) and H. ingrica (figs 5–8) from Moscow Region (Russia): 1, 5 — habitus, male, dorsal view; 2, 6 — habitus, female, dorsal view; 3, 7 — arista, male, lateral view; 4, 8 — thorax, female, ventral view (arrow shows the pilosity of the posterior part of the katepisternum and hind coxa)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6377544" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6377544/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">figs 5–8</figureCitation>
) by the longer body, 9.0– 
<quantity id="4C9F9B02744EFFE0C5D0FA75FDFC981D" box="[475,559,1510,1537]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.3" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" unit="mm" value="13.0">13 mm</quantity>
(in 
<taxonomicName id="4C674D64744EFFE0C66CFA74FD0D981C" authorityName="Stackelberg" authorityYear="1952" box="[615,734,1511,1536]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Hammerschmidtia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ingrica">
<emphasis id="B913EAF5744EFFE0C66CFA74FD0D981C" box="[615,734,1511,1536]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">H. ingrica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, body length 5.5–8.0 mm), and plumose arista (
<figureCitation id="135C2A62744EFFE0C50BF995FEED983D" box="[256,318,1542,1569]" captionStart="Figs 1–8" captionStartId="2.[166,205,1723,1745]" captionTargetBox="[166,1224,261,1679]" captionTargetId="figure-14@2.[166,1225,261,1679]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 1–8. Hammerschmidtia ferruginea (figs 1–4) from Rivne Region (Ukraine) and H. ingrica (figs 5–8) from Moscow Region (Russia): 1, 5 — habitus, male, dorsal view; 2, 6 — habitus, female, dorsal view; 3, 7 — arista, male, lateral view; 4, 8 — thorax, female, ventral view (arrow shows the pilosity of the posterior part of the katepisternum and hind coxa)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6377544" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6377544/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">fig. 3</figureCitation>
), with its branches&gt; 2× as long as the maximum diameter of the arista (in 
<taxonomicName id="4C674D64744EFFE0C4A5F9B4FEF3985C" authorityName="Stackelberg" authorityYear="1952" box="[174,288,1575,1600]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Hammerschmidtia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ingrica">
<emphasis id="B913EAF5744EFFE0C4A5F9B4FEF3985C" box="[174,288,1575,1600]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">H. ingrica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, arista with shorter microtrichia (
<figureCitation id="135C2A62744EFFE0C6A2F9B5FD36985D" box="[681,741,1574,1601]" captionStart="Figs 1–8" captionStartId="2.[166,205,1723,1745]" captionTargetBox="[166,1224,261,1679]" captionTargetId="figure-14@2.[166,1225,261,1679]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 1–8. Hammerschmidtia ferruginea (figs 1–4) from Rivne Region (Ukraine) and H. ingrica (figs 5–8) from Moscow Region (Russia): 1, 5 — habitus, male, dorsal view; 2, 6 — habitus, female, dorsal view; 3, 7 — arista, male, lateral view; 4, 8 — thorax, female, ventral view (arrow shows the pilosity of the posterior part of the katepisternum and hind coxa)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6377544" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6377544/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">fig. 7</figureCitation>
), the longest branches slightly longer than the maximum diameter of the arista). Additionally, 
<taxonomicName id="4C674D64744EFFE0C714F9D4FC6F987C" baseAuthorityName="Fallen" baseAuthorityYear="1817" box="[799,956,1606,1632]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Hammerschmidtia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ferruginea">
<emphasis id="B913EAF5744EFFE0C714F9D4FC6F987C" box="[799,956,1606,1632]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">H. ferruginea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be separated from 
<taxonomicName id="4C674D64744EFFE0C4A5F9F4FEF6989C" authorityName="Stackelberg" authorityYear="1952" box="[174,293,1639,1664]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Hammerschmidtia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ingrica">
<emphasis id="B913EAF5744EFFE0C4A5F9F4FEF6989C" box="[174,293,1639,1664]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">H. ingrica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by: hind coxae covered with numerous short black setae (
<bibRefCitation id="EFF64B16744EFFE0C7E7F9F5FF3B98BD" author="Mutin, V. A. &amp; Barkalov, A. V." pageId="1" pageNumber="18" pagination="342 - 500" refId="ref6373" refString="Mutin, V. A. &amp; Barkalov, A. V. 1999. Fam. Syrphidae - hoverflies. In: Lehr, P. A., ed. Key to the insects of Russian Far East. Vol. 6 (Diptera and Siphonaptera), pt. 1. Dalnauka Publishing House, Vladivostok, 342 - 500 [In Russian]." type="book chapter" year="1999">Mutin &amp; Barkalov, 1999</bibRefCitation>
) as well as katepisternum with several (8–12) long black setae posteriorly (
<figureCitation id="135C2A62744EFFE0C06BF915FB4D98BD" box="[1120,1182,1670,1697]" captionStart="Figs 1–8" captionStartId="2.[166,205,1723,1745]" captionTargetBox="[166,1224,261,1679]" captionTargetId="figure-14@2.[166,1225,261,1679]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 1–8. Hammerschmidtia ferruginea (figs 1–4) from Rivne Region (Ukraine) and H. ingrica (figs 5–8) from Moscow Region (Russia): 1, 5 — habitus, male, dorsal view; 2, 6 — habitus, female, dorsal view; 3, 7 — arista, male, lateral view; 4, 8 — thorax, female, ventral view (arrow shows the pilosity of the posterior part of the katepisternum and hind coxa)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6377544" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6377544/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">fig. 4</figureCitation>
) (in 
<taxonomicName id="4C674D64744EFFE0C4A5F934FEF198DC" authorityName="Stackelberg" authorityYear="1952" box="[174,290,1703,1728]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Hammerschmidtia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ingrica">
<emphasis id="B913EAF5744EFFE0C4A5F934FEF198DC" box="[174,290,1703,1728]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">H. ingrica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, katepisternum without black setae, and hind coxae mostly with 2–3 long black setae only in outer posterior corner laterally and the same amount at the posterior edge, as on 
<figureCitation id="135C2A62744EFFE0C4DEF975FEDC991D" box="[213,271,1766,1793]" captionStart="Figs 1–8" captionStartId="2.[166,205,1723,1745]" captionTargetBox="[166,1224,261,1679]" captionTargetId="figure-14@2.[166,1225,261,1679]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 1–8. Hammerschmidtia ferruginea (figs 1–4) from Rivne Region (Ukraine) and H. ingrica (figs 5–8) from Moscow Region (Russia): 1, 5 — habitus, male, dorsal view; 2, 6 — habitus, female, dorsal view; 3, 7 — arista, male, lateral view; 4, 8 — thorax, female, ventral view (arrow shows the pilosity of the posterior part of the katepisternum and hind coxa)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6377544" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6377544/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">fig. 8</figureCitation>
); female tergite 2 (
<figureCitation id="135C2A62744EFFE0C5E6F975FDF9991D" box="[493,554,1766,1793]" captionStart="Figs 1–8" captionStartId="2.[166,205,1723,1745]" captionTargetBox="[166,1224,261,1679]" captionTargetId="figure-14@2.[166,1225,261,1679]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 1–8. Hammerschmidtia ferruginea (figs 1–4) from Rivne Region (Ukraine) and H. ingrica (figs 5–8) from Moscow Region (Russia): 1, 5 — habitus, male, dorsal view; 2, 6 — habitus, female, dorsal view; 3, 7 — arista, male, lateral view; 4, 8 — thorax, female, ventral view (arrow shows the pilosity of the posterior part of the katepisternum and hind coxa)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6377544" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6377544/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">fig. 2</figureCitation>
) usually with pale anterolateral part that do not look like separate maculae (in 
<taxonomicName id="4C674D64744EFFE0C5A2F894FDCE993C" authorityName="Stackelberg" authorityYear="1952" box="[425,541,1799,1824]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Hammerschmidtia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ingrica">
<emphasis id="B913EAF5744EFFE0C5A2F894FDCE993C" box="[425,541,1799,1824]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">H. ingrica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, female tergites 2 and often 3 with pale maculae that look like a separate maculae (
<figureCitation id="135C2A62744EFFE0C5C1F8B5FDD4995D" box="[458,519,1830,1857]" captionStart="Figs 1–8" captionStartId="2.[166,205,1723,1745]" captionTargetBox="[166,1224,261,1679]" captionTargetId="figure-14@2.[166,1225,261,1679]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 1–8. Hammerschmidtia ferruginea (figs 1–4) from Rivne Region (Ukraine) and H. ingrica (figs 5–8) from Moscow Region (Russia): 1, 5 — habitus, male, dorsal view; 2, 6 — habitus, female, dorsal view; 3, 7 — arista, male, lateral view; 4, 8 — thorax, female, ventral view (arrow shows the pilosity of the posterior part of the katepisternum and hind coxa)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6377544" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6377544/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">fig. 6</figureCitation>
), especially on tergite 2).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<caption id="DF18666F744DFFE3C4ADF928FE1C993D" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6377544" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6377544" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6377544/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="19" startId="2.[166,205,1723,1745]" targetBox="[166,1224,261,1679]" targetPageId="2">
<paragraph id="8BD836E7744DFFE3C4ADF928FE1C993D" blockId="2.[166,1225,1723,1825]" pageId="2" pageNumber="19">
Figs 1–8. 
